<dl id="n42025c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n42" href="#n42025c">N42 (VI.B.31)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n42all.htm#n42025c"> 25(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> solus cum sola <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n42025c"><li>FW 189.19 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n42025c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n42025c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n42025c">MS BL 47475-73</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:513 <a name="gd9" href="../../ff/fdra/gda.htm#gd9">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd9.htm#n42025c">Draft: I.7&sect;1.9</a>/2.9</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In his admirable letter to the Priest Nepotianus, on the life of priests, vol. ii., p. 203, when speaking of the relations of priests with women, he <font color="green">[St. Jerome]</font> says: &ldquo;Solus cum sola, secreto et absque arbitrio, vel teste, non sedeas. &hellip;&rdquo; &ldquo;Never sit in secret, alone in a retired place, with a female who is alone with you. &hellip; <small> Chiniquy, <a name="CPWC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CPWC"><cite title="source">The Priest The Woman and The Confessional</cite></a> (n.d.) 122</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also: <a name="n42014c" href="n42all.htm#n42014c">N42 (VI.B.31):014(c)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
